  <p>
    A septic tank rarely fills without warning. As the sludge and scum layers build, the system
    starts to signal that it is running short on room — and those signals are your chance to
    schedule a routine pump instead of dealing with a backup. The signs below are worth acting on;
    just keep in mind that similar symptoms can have other causes, so they point toward a check
    rather than a certainty.
  </p>

