  <h2>Signs Worth Noticing</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Whole-house slow drains.</strong> One slow sink is usually a local clog; every drain slowing together points at the system.</li>
    <li><strong>Gurgling after water use.</strong> Trapped air escaping through drains and toilets can mean the system isn’t flowing freely.</li>
    <li><strong>Odors indoors or near the tank.</strong> Smells suggest waste isn’t being contained or moved along the way it should.</li>
    <li><strong>Wet or spongy ground over the tank or field.</strong> Soft, soggy areas without recent rain can mean the system is over capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Unusually lush, green grass over the tank or field.</strong> A bright patch can indicate nutrient-rich water reaching the surface.</li>
    <li><strong>It’s simply been a long time.</strong> If you can’t recall the last pump-out, the tank may be closer to full than you think.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why the Level Has to Be Confirmed On Site</h2>
  <p>
    None of these signs measures how full the tank actually is — they only suggest it. Confirming
    the level means opening and measuring the tank, which a provider does during a pump-out or an
    inspection. That is also the moment to learn how full it really was, which helps set your next
    <a href="/how-often-to-pump-septic-tank/">pumping interval</a>. Opening a septic tank yourself
    is hazardous and best left to a provider.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Do Next</h2>
  <p>
    If you’re seeing one or more of these signs, the low-stress move is to have the tank checked
    before it becomes a backup. Describe what you’re noticing and when the system was last serviced,
    and <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> — a provider can confirm the level and
    advise on timing. If you’re already seeing a backup, see
    <a href="/what-to-do-when-sewage-backs-up/">what to do when sewage backs up</a>.
  </p>

